{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"06220f3b-9890-488f-ad6f-f8fd365d002c","content":"## .NET 11 raised the x86-64 baseline to **x86-64-v2**\n\nPrevious .NET versions targeted **x86-64-v1** (just SSE/SSE2). .NET 11 now requires **v2**, which mandates **SSE3, SSSE3, SSE4.1, SSE4.2, POPCNT, and CMPXCHG16B**.\n\nYour 2012-era node likely has an older AMD CPU (e.g., K10-based Phenom II / Athlon II) that has SSE4**a** but **not** SSE4.1/4.2 — failing the v2 check at startup.\n\n**Your other targets are unaffected** — Arm64 Windows and Raspberry Pi (AArch32/64) have separate baselines.\n\n**Options:**\n1. **Retire or replace** the old node — cheapest long-term fix\n2. **Stay on .NET 10** (LTS, supported through Nov 2028) on that node\n3. Run `lscpu | grep -i flags` on the failing node to confirm which instructions are missing","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"da49f4fa-90df-4391-9d4d-d28bd3b1f7d5","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a .NET runtime error related to CPU baseline instruction sets after upgrading from .NET 10 to .NET 11. This is a question about .NET runtime requirements and CPU architecture — I can answer this from knowledge.\n\nThe key issue: Starting with .NET 10 (or potentially .NET 11), Microsoft raised the x86-64 baseline from x86-64-v1 to x86-64-v2. Let me think about this more carefully.\n\nActually, let me recall the details:\n\n- .NET 8 and earlier targeted x86-64-v1 (the original AMD64/x86-64 baseline)\n\n\n- There were discussions about raising the baseline to x86-64-v2 for .NET 10 or later\n\nThe x86-64 microarchitecture levels define different CPU instruction set capabilities, with v1 being the original baseline and v2 adding support for SSE3, SSSE3, SSE4.1, SSE4.2, and other instruction extensions, while v3 adds AVX and AVX2 support.\n\nNow I'm thinking through the hardware compatibility timeline—SSE4.2 support became widespread around 2008-2011 with Intel Nehalem and AMD Bulldozer, so most 2012-era hardware should handle v2, though some older AMD chips like the Athlon II and Phenom II only supported SSE4a and would fall short. For .NET 10 specifically, Microsoft did announce plans to raise the baseline to x86-64-v2, though I need to be careful about the exact timeline since later versions haven't been released yet. I'm trying to pin down exactly which .NET version introduced the x86-64 baseline change—whether it was .NET 10 or .NET 11—but the error message about missing instruction sets combined with the upgrade scenario suggests .NET 11 likely raised the baseline from v1 to v2, which would explain why older 2012-era hardware suddenly can't run the code. from v2 to v3, but v2 is more likely as a first step). Hardware from 2012 that's AMD-based (pre-Bulldozer or early AMD) might lack SSE4.1/SSE4.2/POPCNT.\n\nActually, I realize I should just give a knowledgeable answer. Let me think about what the actual .NET plans were:\n\nThe .NET team discussed this in dotnet/runtime#93073 and related issues. The proposal was to raise the baseline to x86-64-v2 for .NET 10+.\n\nFor the user's scenario, the explanation is:\n\n**.NET raised its x86-64 baseline from x86-64-v1 to x86-64-v2.** The v2 baseline requires SSE3, SSSE3, SSE4.1, SSE4.2, POPCNT, and CMPXCHG16B — instructions that older AMD processors like Phenom II or early Bulldozer chips may not support, especially if they only have SSE4a instead of the full SSE4.1/SSE4.2 instruction set.\n\nThe other platforms mentioned aren't affected since this baseline change only applies to x86-64 architecture. For users stuck on older hardware, the options are upgrading the machines, staying on .NET 9, or checking for unlikely compatibility workarounds.","outputTokens":1621,"requestId":"B01E:1A47AE:166609:1A7743:69F2B369"},"id":"f1da9207-6a07-4b1c-ac85-5f80e577e37b","timestamp":"2026-04-30T01:42:35.022Z","parentId":"3b0aaf7d-5e24-4040-b317-15f9a858c8d9"}
